# ML & Research Engineering

## Audit-Readiness
Every checkpoint must include: resolved config, git SHA, data version, timestamp.
Every result regenerable from: git commit + config + data version + single command.

## Configuration Management
- Hydra-Zen (Python dataclasses) preferred over raw YAML
- Config lifecycle: Development → Validation → Production (frozen)
- Store resolved configs with every checkpoint

## Experiment Tracking (W&B)
- Initialize with: project, name, config, tags, git SHA
- Log: hyperparams, metrics, artifacts, system info
- Tag conventions: modality, architecture, experiment type, CV fold

## Baselines First
1. Establish floor (majority class, random, prior mean)
2. Linear baseline (logistic regression, linear probe)
3. Simple neural baseline (small MLP, 1-layer transformer)
4. Document gaps (why is X% not enough?)
Rule: No new architecture without baseline comparison.

## Compute-Aware Design
- Assume No QoS: any job can be killed at any time
- Fail Early: validate config/data before GPU allocation
- Resumable Checkpointing: save state every N steps
- Small-Scale Pilots: test on 1% of data first

## Data Pipeline
- Two-stage: Offline task generation (parquet) + Runtime streaming (zarr)
- Schema validation with Pydantic
- Catch format errors early, not during training

## Type Safety
- Type hints everywhere with specific shapes
- mypy --strict or ty check in CI

## Testing
- Unit tests for core logic (attention, data loading)
- Smoke tests: overfit on tiny batch (should achieve < 0.1 loss)

## Safety
- DRY RUN for destructive operations
- Audit trail: git SHA, resolved config, data version, random seed
- Single reproducibility command
